# Backend HTTP vs gRPC Ports

## REST / public HTTP

- **Only `frontend-api`** exposes HTTP for platform **REST API**.
- No REST controllers, public HTTP routes, or "second gateways" on other `backend/apps/*` for client-facing APIs.

## Inter-process communication

- **All other apps** talk via **gRPC** (gRPC server ports).
- Prefer gRPC clients from `frontend-api` (and other callers) to backend services; no HTTP client-to-service APIs on non–`frontend-api` apps.

## Ports and deployment

- **Do not** publish/document HTTP listen ports for non–`frontend-api` as product API surface (Docker compose, K8s Services, Postman "REST" for internal services, etc.).
- Internal tooling (health, metrics, debug) follows existing patterns; no extra HTTP exposure beyond convention.

## When changing APIs

- New/changed **gRPC** contracts: implement in owning service, expose REST via **`frontend-api`** (see `api-postman-sync.mdc`).
